        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe stepwise formation constants (log Kв‚Ѓ = 6.35, log ОІв‚‚ = 11.67, giving log Kв‚‚ в‰€ 5.32) show the expected decrease for the second histidine binding step, consistent with statistical and steric effects at the zinc centre. The protonation constants of the complexes (log K в‰€ 4.6вЂ“5.5) reflect protonation of the imidazole nitrogen in the coordinated histidine, which is notably lower than the free-ligand imidazole pKв‚ђ (~6.05). This acidification upon coordination to ZnВІвЃє is a well-known effect of metal-ion binding. The choice of 37 В°C and physiological-like ionic strength (0.15 M) indicates the study was designed to model biologically relevant conditions вЂ” appropriate given histidine's prominent role as a zinc-binding residue in metalloproteins such as carbonic anhydrase and zinc-finger domains.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
